  "prompt_text": "Describe what gratitude feels like in the body — not the concept, but the physical and emotional sensation.",
  "response_text": "Gratitude often brings a warm, comforting sensation that starts in the chest area and can spread throughout the body. Physically, it might feel like a gentle pressure or warmth, sometimes described as a \"warm glow\" or \"butterflies.\" This feeling can be accompanied by a lightness in the heart and a sense of relief or release. Emotionally, gratitude is often associated with a deep sense of contentment and peace. It can lead to a reduction in stress hormones and an increase in positive emotions such as joy and happiness. The mind may feel more clear and open, and there's often a sense of connection to others and the world around you.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 8\nV (Verbal Fluency): 9\nG (Goal Directedness): 7\nP (Pattern Recognition): 9\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 9\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 8\n---END RATINGS---",
